Reference Canon
Α complete, consolidated reference canon as it now stands. 
Political Thought, Power, and Legitimacy
Václav Havel Living in truth. Post-totalitarian power. Systems collapse when people withdraw moral participation.
Hannah Arendt Banality of evil. Bureaucracy as diffusion of responsibility. Administration replacing judgment.
Alexis de Tocqueville Soft despotism. Civic erosion under centralisation. Loss of agency without overt tyranny.
John Locke Consent, stewardship, limits of authority. Property as responsibility rather than extraction.
Niccolò Machiavelli Power as it actually operates, not as it is idealised. Necessary counterpoint to moral theory.

Economics, Money, and Constraint
Austrian School of Economics Time preference, capital structure, irreversibility, limits of central planning.
Ludwig von Mises Economic calculation problem. Information loss under abstraction.
Friedrich Hayek Distributed knowledge. Fatal conceit. Prices as signals, not commands.
Silvio Gesell Money as flow versus store. Hoarding paradox. Time embedded in currency.
John Maynard Keynes Liquidity preference. Psychological time horizons. Useful foil to Austrian critique.
John Nash Equilibrium under constraint. Stability without optimisation. Non-cooperative systems.
Elinor Ostrom Commons governance. Polycentric authority. Stewardship without ownership.

Ecology, Land, and Living Systems
Allan Savory Holistic decision making. Context before prescription. Unintended consequences of reductionism.
Savory Institute Ecological monitoring beyond carbon. Soil, water, biodiversity, resilience.
Aldo Leopold Land ethic. Moral extension to soil, water, plants, and animals.
James Lovelock Earth as a self-regulating system. Feedback loops and planetary limits.
Eugene Odum Energy flows, succession, ecosystem maturity, and constraint.

Humanities, Meaning, and Human Behaviour
Viktor Frankl Meaning under constraint. Responsibility as the last freedom.
Albert Camus The absurd. Refusal without nihilism. Dignity under indifferent systems.
Fyodor Dostoevsky Moral psychology. Freedom versus security. The danger of removing burden.
Joseph Campbell Archetypes. Cyclical narratives. Myth as compressed truth across generations.

Science, Systems, and Paradox
Werner Heisenberg Observer effect. Limits of measurement. Uncertainty as structural, not error.
Ilya Prigogine Dissipative structures. Order emerging from entropy under constraint.
Norbert Wiener Feedback, control, and failure in closed systems.

Wisdom Traditions and Restraint Doctrine
Solomon Proverbs, Ecclesiastes. False scales, haste to wealth, limits before optimisation.
Gautama Buddha The Middle Way. Rejection of extremes. Non-attachment as system stability.

Indigenous Knowledge and Custodianship
Lakota people Intergenerational custodianship. Land held in trust, never owned. Authority accountable to the unborn.
Southern African customary law and stewardship traditions Right of Use over ownership. Ancestral accountability. Land as relational, not transactional.
Totemic and kinship systems Identity as ecological relationship. Governance embedded in lineage and place.
Oral history and place-based witnessing Memory encoded in landscape, ritual, and continuity rather than documents.

The Unifying Thread
Across all of this, the invariant principles repeat:
Constraint precedes optimisation.
Authority without restraint decays.
Meaning survives only where burden is real.
Systems fail morally before they fail mechanically.
Time is the final auditor.
Different cultures. Different languages. Same truth, rediscovered at the edge of collapse.
